definition.value: Interacting with a death receptor such that the proportion of death receptors in an active form is increased. Ligand binding to a death receptor often induces a conformational change to activate the receptor.
Combining with a bile acid and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity. A bile acid is any member of a group of steroid carboxylic acids occurring in bile.

label.value: G-protein coupled bile acid receptor activity

definition.value: Combining with an extracellular bile acid and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein -  promotes the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein complex.
Combining with lithocholic acid and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with a pathogen-associated molecular pattern (PAMP), a structure conserved among microbial species, or damage-associated molecular pattern (DAMP), an endogenous molecule released from damaged cells), to initiate a change in cell activity.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a member of the neuropilin family.
A heterodimeric protein complex that binds a type I interferon and transmits the signal across the membrane into the cell. Consists of an alpha subunit (IFNAR1) and a beta subunit (IFNAR2).
Combining with auxin and transmitting the signal in the cell to initiate a change in cell activity. Auxin is a plant hormone (phytohormone).
Combining with ethylene and transmitting the signal in the cell to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with ethylene and transmitting the signal within the cell to initiate a change in cell activity by catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + a protein-L-histidine -eq- ADP + a protein-L-histidine phosphate.

A protein complex that contains at least TOR (target of rapamycin) in complex with other signaling components. Mediates the phosphorylation and activation of downstream signaling components including PKB (AKT) or S6K.

label.value: suppression by virus of host RNA polymerase II activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of host RNA polymerase II activity.

label.value: suppression by virus of host mRNA processing

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA processing in the host cell. mRNA processing is the conversion of a primary mRNA transcript into one or more mature mRNA(s) prior to translation into polypeptide.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF3 activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF3 (interferon regulatory factor-3), a transcription factor in the RIG-I|MDA-5 signaling pathway. Viral infection triggers phosphorylation of cytoplasmic IRF3, which allows IRF3 to form a homodimer, migrate to the nucleus, and activate transcription of IFN-alpha and IFN-beta genes.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF3 activity by inhibition of IRF3 phosphorylation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of the phosphorylation of IRF3 (interferon regulatory factor-3), thereby inhibiting IRF3 activation. In response to signaling from RIG-1|MDA-5 receptors, IRF3 is phosphorylated on multiple serine and threonine residues -  phosphorylation results in the cytoplasm-to-nucleus translocation of IRF3, DNA binding, and increased transcriptional activation of interferon-encoding genes.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF3 activity by inhibition of DNA binding

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces IRF3-dependent gene transcription, by preventing or reducing IRF3 binding to promoter sites.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF3 activity by positive regulation of IRF3 catabolic process

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF3 (interferon regulatory factor-3) by promoting the ubiquitin-dependent degradation of IRF3, mediated by the proteasome.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with RIG-I, a cytosolic pattern recognition receptor that initiates an antiviral signaling pathway upon binding to viral RNA.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with MDA-5, a cytosolic pattern recognition receptor that initiates an antiviral signaling pathway upon binding to viral dsRNA.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF7 activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF7 (interferon regulatory factor-7), a transcription factor in the RIG-I|MDA-5 signaling pathway. Viral infection triggers phosphorylation of cytoplasmic IRF7, which allows IRF7 to form a homodimer, migrate to the nucleus, and activate transcription of IFN-alpha and IFN-beta genes.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF7 activity by positive regulation of IRF7 sumoylation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces IRF7-dependent gene transcription, by promoting the sumoylation of IRF7, thereby disabling its activity.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF7 activity by positive regulation of IRF7 catabolic process

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF7 (interferon regulatory factor-7) by promoting the ubiquitin-dependent degradation of IRF7, mediated by the proteasome.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF9 activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF9 (interferon regulatory factor-9), a transcription factor involved in the innate immune response. Viral infection triggers binding of IRF9 to phosphorylated STAT1 and STAT2, forming the ISGF3 complex. The ISGF3 complex migrates to the nucleus and activates transcription of IFN-responsive genes.

label.value: suppression by virus of host IRF9 activity by positive regulation of IRF9 localization to nucleus

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the activity of host IRF9 (interferon regulatory factor-9) by promoting the nuclear accumulation of IRF9. For example, the reovirus mu2 protein promotes nuclear accumulation of host IRF9 by an as yet unconfirmed-mechanism.

label.value: endoribonuclease activity involved in viral induction of host mRNA catabolic process

definition.value: Any endoribonuclease activity that contributes to the viral-induced catabolism of host mRNA.

label.value: cleavage by virus of host mRNA

definition.value: Any process in which a host pre-mRNA or mRNA molecule is cleaved at specific sites or in a regulated manner by a viral endoribonuclease.

label.value: suppression by virus of host transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Any process in which a virus stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the assembly of the RNA polymerase II preinitiation complex (PIC) at an RNA polymerase II promoter region of a host DNA template.

label.value: TBP-class protein binding involved in viral suppression of host transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Selective and non-covalent interaction of a viral protein with a member of the class of TATA-binding proteins (TBP) in the host, including any of the TBP-related factors (TRFs), which contributes to the viral-suppression of assembly of the RNA polymerase II preinitiation complex (PIC) at an RNA polymerase II promoter region of a host DNA template.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of translation of host mRNA.

label.value: TFIIB-class transcription factor binding involved in viral suppression of host transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Selective and non-covalent interaction of a viral protein with a member of the TFIIB-class of host transcription factors, which contributes to the viral-suppression of assembly of the RNA polymerase II preinitiation complex (PIC) at an RNA polymerase II promoter region of a host DNA template.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of host translation initiation, the host process preceding formation of the peptide bond between the first two amino acids of a protein.

label.value: proteolysis by virus of host translation initiation factor

definition.value: The chemical reactions and pathways performed by a virus resulting in the hydrolysis of a host translation initiation factor by cleavage of its peptide bonds.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation factor activity by induction of host protein dephosphorylation

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a host translation initiation factor by promoting dephosphorylation of a host protein.

label.value: suppression by virus of host translation initiation factor activity

definition.value: Any process in which a virus prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a host translation initiation factor.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-1 symmetry. The T-eq-1 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-2 symmetry. The T-eq-2 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric dimers.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-3 symmetry. The T-eq-3 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with pseudo T-eq-3 symmetry. The T-eq-pseudo3 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-4 symmetry. The T-eq-4 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 30 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-7 symmetry. The T-eq-7 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 60 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-13 symmetry. The T-eq-13 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 120 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-16 symmetry. The T-eq-16 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 150 hexameric capsomeres.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-25 symmetry. The T-eq-25 capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 240 hexameric capsomeres.
The outer layer of a double or triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Outer capsids are part of reoviridae and cystoviridae virions.
The inner layer of a double or triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Inner capsids are part of reoviridae and cystoviridae virions.
The intermediate layer of a triple concentric icosahedral capsid. Intermediate capsids are part of reoviridae virions.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-147 symmetry. T-eq-147 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 1460 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 8820 capsid proteins.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-169 symmetry. T-eq-169 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 1680 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 10140 capsid proteins.

The protein coat that surrounds the infective nucleic acid in some virus particles where the subunits (capsomeres) are arranged to form an icosahedron with T-eq-219 symmetry. T-eq-219 icosahedral capsid is composed of 12 pentameric and 2180 hexameric capsomeres for a total of 13140 capsid proteins.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + H2O -eq- ADP + phosphate, to drive movement along a single- or double-stranded RNA molecule.
